cs.CL, cs.AI, cs.LG, cs.SD, cs.NE 

This paper is about dialogue policy learning in task-completion dialogue systems, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP) and machine learning. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). Additionally, the paper uses a generative adversarial network (GAN) inspired approach, which is a popular technique in deep learning and artificial intelligence, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) another likely category. The paper also proposes a new method to improve the efficiency of dialogue policy learning, which involves training a discriminator and incorporating it into the advantage actor-critic (A2C) framework. This suggests that the paper could also be categorized under cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Finally, the paper presents experimental results in a specific domain, which could potentially fall under cs.SD (Software Engineering).
